  "opinion": "As a journalist who’s spent years covering education and diversity issues in Washington, DC, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat—not just a theoretical concept but a lived reality—impacts students and professionals in STEM fields. Stereotype threat occurs when individuals internalize negative stereotypes about their group, leading to anxiety that undermines their performance. For example, when a young woman in a coding class starts to doubt her ability because she’s reminded of the 'math isn’t for girls' narrative, her focus shifts from problem-solving to self-doubt. This isn’t just about individual confidence; it’s about systemic barriers that prevent underrepresented groups from thriving. In my work, I’ve observed how this manifests in classrooms where students from marginalized backgrounds avoid participating in group discussions, fearing judgment. Addressing stereotype threat isn’t a one-size-fits-all solution. It requires intentional, culturally responsive teaching that validates students’ identities and builds a sense of belonging. Schools and institutions must create environments where diversity is celebrated, not just tolerated. For instance, mentorship programs that pair students with role models from similar backgrounds can alleviate anxiety and foster resilience. Additionally, curricula that highlight diverse contributions to STEM—like the work of women in engineering or people of color in data science—can challenge harmful stereotypes and inspire confidence. As someone who’s raised three children and navigated my own path as a creative professional, I know that change starts with empathy and active listening. We must move beyond surface-level diversity initiatives to address the root causes of stereotype threat. By doing so, we don’t just improve academic outcomes; we build a more equitable future for all. The time to act is now.",
